    text: "Rivers are flowing bodies of fresh water that move continuously downhill from areas of higher elevation toward areas of lower elevation until they eventually empty into oceans, lakes, or other rivers. They begin their journeys as small trickles and streams fed by melting mountain snow, natural underground springs, or rainfall that collects in high places and begins to flow downhill. As water moves from higher to lower ground, smaller streams and creeks join together and merge, forming progressively larger and more powerful rivers. The place where a river begins its journey is called its source, and the place where it empties into a larger body of water at the end of its journey is called its mouth. The Nile River in northeastern Africa holds the distinction of being the longest river on Earth, stretching more than four thousand miles from its source in East Africa all the way to the Mediterranean Sea in the north. The Amazon River in South America, while slightly shorter, carries more water than any other river on Earth, discharging an enormous volume of fresh water into the Atlantic Ocean every single second. Rivers have played an absolutely central role in shaping human civilization throughout history, because they provide fresh water for drinking, cooking, and irrigating farmland in regions that might otherwise be too dry to support large numbers of people. Some of the oldest and most sophisticated civilizations in the ancient world, including those of Egypt, Mesopotamia, the Indus Valley, and ancient China, all grew up along the banks of major rivers that provided the reliable water supply needed to support large farming populations. Rivers naturally carve and reshape the land over time through a slow process called erosion, wearing away rock and soil and depositing it downstream, gradually cutting valleys and canyons. The most dramatic example of this process is the Grand Canyon in Arizona, which was carved by the Colorado River over a period of roughly five to six million years. Today rivers around the world face serious threats from industrial pollution, plastic waste, the construction of dams, and the overextraction of water for agriculture and cities.",
